00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:38.820
When I first went
on tour, I started

00:01:38.820 --> 00:01:40.920
talking a lot about my
books at the speeches.

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:43.020
But then I started to
realize that everyone

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:45.180
who was at my
signings already had

00:01:45.180 --> 00:01:46.860
the book I was talking about.

00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:49.270
So I didn't really
need to do a hard sell.

00:01:49.270 --> 00:01:52.430
So instead, I started
thinking about they give me

00:01:52.430 --> 00:01:53.050
this platform.

00:01:53.050 --> 00:01:55.054
I'm a university professor.

00:01:55.054 --> 00:01:56.720
You give me a microphone
and a platform,

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:58.540
I'll start talking about stuff.

00:01:58.540 --> 00:02:00.829
I started just talking a
little bit about whatever I

00:02:00.829 --> 00:02:02.120
was thinking about at the time.

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:04.050
And it does usually
relate a little bit

00:02:04.050 --> 00:02:05.842
to my writing in some way.

00:02:05.842 --> 00:02:07.550
It's just whatever's
been inside my head.

00:02:07.550 --> 00:02:09.440
People like to reach
in there and be like,

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.070
oh, this is what the
author is thinking about.

00:02:12.070 --> 00:02:15.610
And my story, actually,
this time starts in Sharjah.

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:18.370
Does anyone know
where Sharjah is?

00:02:18.370 --> 00:02:20.420
Oh, smart people in this room.

00:02:20.420 --> 00:02:22.649
I had no idea where
Sharjah was when

00:02:22.649 --> 00:02:24.440
they wrote me and said,
hey, would you like

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:26.070
to come to our book festival.

00:02:26.070 --> 00:02:28.810
Turns out Sharjah is one of
the United Arab Emirates.

00:02:28.810 --> 00:02:31.610
So you've heard of Dubai
and Abu Dhabi, most likely.

00:02:31.610 --> 00:02:34.320
Sharjah is next door to them.

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:38.440
And you know, I get invitations
to book festivals quite a lot.

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:41.710
And I got this one
and said, free trip?

00:02:41.710 --> 00:02:42.320
Sure.

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:44.260
I mean, I've never been
to the Middle East before.

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:46.093
And the United Arab
Emirates are right there

00:02:46.093 --> 00:02:48.930
on the Arabian Peninsula,
right next to Saudi Arabia.

00:02:48.930 --> 00:02:51.310
I thought, this
will be super cool.

00:02:51.310 --> 00:02:53.270
I don't know if anyone
there reads my books.

00:02:53.270 --> 00:02:55.680
Often, you get invitations
to these festivals

00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:57.440
just because they're
looking and saying,

00:02:57.440 --> 00:02:59.150
who is someone we
haven't had yet?

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:01.350
Him.

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:04.405
But it sounded like
it was a fun time.

00:03:04.405 --> 00:03:05.030
And I said yes.

00:03:05.030 --> 00:03:08.380
And indeed, over there--
if you get a chance,

00:03:08.380 --> 00:03:10.920
the United Arab
Emirates is awesome.

00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:12.720
I got to go out and
see the sand dunes.

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:13.219
Right?

00:03:13.219 --> 00:03:17.440
These enormous-- we flew in
a helicopter for 45 minutes

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:17.940
over them.

00:03:17.940 --> 00:03:18.815
They're just endless.

00:03:18.815 --> 00:03:19.730
Right?

00:03:19.730 --> 00:03:22.470
Over to the Arabian
border, and I

00:03:22.470 --> 00:03:25.430
took lots of pictures of myself
on top of giant sand dunes

00:03:25.430 --> 00:03:28.030
making Arrakis jokes.

00:03:28.030 --> 00:03:29.030
You can tell I'm a nerd.

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:30.210
It's not Lawrence of Arabia.

00:03:30.210 --> 00:03:32.210
It's like, walk
without rhythm, guys.

00:03:32.210 --> 00:03:34.890
Sand worms will eat you.

00:03:34.890 --> 00:03:39.405
But then it came time
to go to my signing.

00:03:39.405 --> 00:03:42.875
And I was a little apprehensive
because you go to a signing,

00:03:42.875 --> 00:03:45.000
you're never sure if anyone's
was going to show up.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.700
And you go to a signing
in a foreign country,

00:03:47.700 --> 00:03:50.560
you're extra uncertain
what it's going to be like,

00:03:50.560 --> 00:03:51.680
what the expectations are.

00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:53.154
And I walk into
the big hall where

00:03:53.154 --> 00:03:54.320
they're having the signings.

00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:56.080
And there's this
big line of people.

00:03:56.080 --> 00:03:59.360
And they're wearing traditional
Emirati clothing, which

00:03:59.360 --> 00:04:01.520
means for the women, they
wear the hi-jab, which

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:04.690
is the head scarf that leaves
the face open, the black one.

00:04:04.690 --> 00:04:06.330
And they were wearing
the black dress.

00:04:06.330 --> 00:04:08.340
And then the men are
wearing the thobe,

00:04:08.340 --> 00:04:10.436
which is the white garments.

00:04:10.436 --> 00:04:12.060
And then they have
their own headdress.

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:15.310
And it looks all very formal
and kind of intimidating.

00:04:15.310 --> 00:04:18.470
And yet, they're all
holding huge stacks

00:04:18.470 --> 00:04:23.680
of Brandon Sanderson
novels, these big stacks.

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:25.180
I mean, I feel so
bad for people.

00:04:25.180 --> 00:04:26.221
They come to my signings.

00:04:26.221 --> 00:04:27.990
My books kind of are big.

00:04:27.990 --> 00:04:30.070
And so they're
lugging them along.

00:04:30.070 --> 00:04:33.130
But I stopped and I look
at this big line of people,

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:35.720
and I think it's my people.

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:36.820
Right?

00:04:36.820 --> 00:04:37.757
I've come home.

00:04:37.757 --> 00:04:40.090
I've traveled across the world
to a completely different

00:04:40.090 --> 00:04:40.730
culture.

00:04:40.730 --> 00:04:43.930
And I found the
science fiction nerds.

00:04:43.930 --> 00:04:46.140
And it was really
this wonderful moment

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:49.750
where I thought about the power
of storytelling and fiction

00:04:49.750 --> 00:04:50.910
to connect people.

00:04:50.910 --> 00:04:52.700
Here, I had somehow
made a connection

00:04:52.700 --> 00:04:55.300
with people in a very
different culture from my own

00:04:55.300 --> 00:04:57.520
writing these stories.

00:04:57.520 --> 00:04:58.430
I sat in the line.

00:04:58.430 --> 00:05:01.927
We got to talk about our
favorite Star Trek captains.

00:05:01.927 --> 00:05:04.010
There was one woman there
who had just gotten back

00:05:04.010 --> 00:05:06.740
from comic-con in Dubai.

00:05:06.740 --> 00:05:09.150
And it was really cool.

00:05:09.150 --> 00:05:10.470
She did a cosplay.

00:05:10.470 --> 00:05:12.740
She dressed as the
character No-Face

00:05:12.740 --> 00:05:16.070
from the Miyazaki film, which
is this character who is all

00:05:16.070 --> 00:05:17.383
black with a white face mask.

00:05:17.383 --> 00:05:18.850
She just put a face mask on.

00:05:18.850 --> 00:05:20.100
She's like, I did it.

00:05:20.100 --> 00:05:22.230
It was so easy!

00:05:22.230 --> 00:05:26.570
It was an amazing, amazing
moment, just thinking about,

00:05:26.570 --> 00:05:27.070
like I said.

00:05:27.070 --> 00:05:28.240
That power of fiction.

00:05:28.240 --> 00:05:31.850
I can read a book written
3,000 years ago by someone

00:05:31.850 --> 00:05:33.000
on a different continent.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.020
And I can feel the same
emotions they were feeling

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:37.710
when they wrote that story.

00:05:37.710 --> 00:05:40.510
And that is absolutely amazing.

00:05:40.510 --> 00:05:43.800
And so this led
me, as is natural,

00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:46.490
to thinking about
King Sejong the Great.

00:05:46.490 --> 00:05:47.750
Right?

00:05:47.750 --> 00:05:49.820
That's where you
guys went, right?

00:05:49.820 --> 00:05:50.520
King Sejong.

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:52.990
King Sejong is one my
favorite people in history.

00:05:52.990 --> 00:05:56.230
He was king of
Korea in the 1400s.

00:05:56.230 --> 00:05:59.450
And Sejong, when
he rose to power,

00:05:59.450 --> 00:06:03.000
he had this really interesting
problem he wanted to solve.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.950
And he did this in secret.

00:06:04.950 --> 00:06:07.300
He gathered a bunch
of scholars together.

00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:08.780
Very secret, very hush-hush.

00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:13.530
It was like "Mission Impossible"
with Confucian scholar kings.

00:06:13.530 --> 00:06:15.390
And he gets his
scholars together.

00:06:15.390 --> 00:06:18.520
And he says, I want to
come up with a writing

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:21.260
system for my people.

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:25.490
Now, the thing is, back then
and still commonly in Asia,

00:06:25.490 --> 00:06:29.640
but back then, you wrote Korean
using Chinese characters.

00:06:29.640 --> 00:06:32.280
Does anyone here speak Chinese?

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:33.410
A few of you.

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:37.910
So I apologize for what
I'm about to do to Chinese.

00:06:37.910 --> 00:06:39.160
And I don't know simplified.

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:40.230
I only know complex.

00:06:40.230 --> 00:06:42.310
And I'm not very good at it.

00:06:42.310 --> 00:06:45.120
But Chinese is this
really cool writing system

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:48.320
because what we Chinese is
what we call logographic.

00:06:48.320 --> 00:06:49.760
At least, it's
mostly logographic.

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:54.700
That means that each Chinese
character represents an idea

00:06:54.700 --> 00:06:57.410
rather than being
something phonetic

00:06:57.410 --> 00:06:59.630
that you can sound out.

00:06:59.630 --> 00:07:02.220
And this pen is not
working terribly well.

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:02.787
But it's OK.

00:07:02.787 --> 00:07:04.620
And there's not supposed
to be one of those.

00:07:04.620 --> 00:07:05.810
This one's better?

00:07:05.810 --> 00:07:08.000
OK, I'll let you take that one.

00:07:10.650 --> 00:07:11.830
Oh, that is way better.

00:07:11.830 --> 00:07:13.990
If you want to
write, for instance,

00:07:13.990 --> 00:07:17.970
"Korea," you have to
write it like this.

00:07:17.970 --> 00:07:20.450
That's "Korea" in
Chinese characters,

00:07:20.450 --> 00:07:23.010
written very poorly.

00:07:23.010 --> 00:07:28.145
Now, the great thing about
this is, whatever your language

00:07:28.145 --> 00:07:29.960
is, you can read this
in your language,

00:07:29.960 --> 00:07:31.270
if you know the characters.

00:07:31.270 --> 00:07:32.610
So if you show this
to someone in Japan,

00:07:32.610 --> 00:07:34.130
they'll be like, oh,
that means "Korea."

00:07:34.130 --> 00:07:35.410
If you show it to
someone in China,

00:07:35.410 --> 00:07:37.420
you show it to someone in Korea,
show it to someone in Thailand,

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:40.110
someone in Mongolia, it
crosses cultural boundaries

00:07:40.110 --> 00:07:43.400
really well because
the characters just

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:45.350
represent an idea.

00:07:45.350 --> 00:07:52.700
But the big problem with Chinese
is that you can't sound it out,

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:54.980
which means that for
King Sejong's people, who

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:59.510
were mostly farmers,
not scholars,

00:07:59.510 --> 00:08:02.160
memorizing thousands of these
things to be able to read

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:03.080
was very tough.

00:08:03.080 --> 00:08:04.820
So his people were
completely illiterate.

00:08:04.820 --> 00:08:09.220
And beyond that, can write
Chinese really well in this,

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:09.940
obviously.

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:12.020
But writing Korean is
difficult because Korean

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:15.040
has different conjugation
and structure than Chinese.

00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.190
And so it's like, how do you
write the Korean conjugation.

00:08:18.190 --> 00:08:18.960
You just can't.

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:21.230
You can't write
Korean possessives.

00:08:21.230 --> 00:08:24.220
Korean, when you
write it out, whatever

00:08:24.220 --> 00:08:26.680
your subject is, you put a
little marker on it to say,

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:27.970
this is our subject.

00:08:27.970 --> 00:08:29.580
You write like [SPEAKS KOREAN].

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:32.260
You can't write that
with the Chinese.

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:34.860
You either have to
write in caveman speak.

00:08:34.860 --> 00:08:37.612
Or you have to add in all these
characters that don't actually

00:08:37.612 --> 00:08:38.820
mean what they say they mean.

00:08:38.820 --> 00:08:40.630
And it gets really confusing.

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:43.429
And so King Sejong said,
I want to solve this.

00:08:43.429 --> 00:08:45.390
We're going to
come up with a way

00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:50.310
to write Korean that
works with the Chinese.

00:08:50.310 --> 00:08:52.430
And they came up with
something really ingenious.

00:08:52.430 --> 00:08:55.480
It's called Hangul.

00:08:55.480 --> 00:09:01.990
And Hangul is this thing where
you create a phonetic version

00:09:01.990 --> 00:09:03.280
of a Chinese character.

00:09:03.280 --> 00:09:05.840
This is [SPEAKS  KOREAN]
Hangul, Korea.

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:10.950
And you put these together in
these syllable blocks, where

00:09:10.950 --> 00:09:14.070
you construct something that
would work in the same writing

00:09:14.070 --> 00:09:17.110
system with the Chinese, which
is really nifty because what

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:19.030
you can do is you can
still write in Chinese

00:09:19.030 --> 00:09:22.820
and then add the Korean letters
to give the conjugation if you

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:23.460
want to.

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:25.500
Or you can just write
straight in Korean

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:27.600
and write it exactly
the same way.

00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:29.820
Or you can drop in the
occasional cool Chinese

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:33.177
character to look awesome, which
is what people do these days.

00:09:33.177 --> 00:09:35.510
If you want to be cool, you
write some words in Chinese.

00:09:35.510 --> 00:09:37.030
You're like,
yeah,yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:09:37.030 --> 00:09:38.520
And then the rest
is all in Korean

00:09:38.520 --> 00:09:43.370
because Chinese just looks
beautiful on the page.

00:09:43.370 --> 00:09:46.300
So King Sejong
came up with this.

00:09:46.300 --> 00:09:49.070
It is amazing how
well this works.

00:09:49.070 --> 00:09:52.320
In fact, Korea is one of
the most literate countries

00:09:52.320 --> 00:09:55.050
in the world today, partially
because of how great

00:09:55.050 --> 00:09:56.570
this writing system is.

00:09:56.570 --> 00:09:58.750
Linguists just drool
over this writing system.

00:09:58.750 --> 00:09:59.617
It is so nifty.

00:09:59.617 --> 00:10:01.450
There's lots of really
cool things about it.

00:10:01.450 --> 00:10:05.310
But he presents it to his court
after they come up with it.

00:10:05.310 --> 00:10:07.100
And they hated it.

00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:08.280
They absolutely hated it.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:12.320
In fact, one of the people in
court wrote, "How could this

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:15.120
not to be a setback
to our civilization?

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:16.990
Spending too much thought
and effort on this

00:10:16.990 --> 00:10:19.820
is a waste of time detrimental
to the timely pursuit

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:22.320
of scholarship."

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:23.510
Yeah.

00:10:23.510 --> 00:10:26.640
So this cool system
that is brilliant

00:10:26.640 --> 00:10:28.650
and since then has
been widely regarded

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:32.936
as one of the best
alphabets ever invented,

00:10:32.936 --> 00:10:34.810
in fact, I think the
only major alphabet that

00:10:34.810 --> 00:10:39.000
was designed by scholars rather
than arising accidentally.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.270
So why did they hate it?

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:43.915
Any guesses?

00:10:43.915 --> 00:10:45.832
AUDIENCE: It made
scholarship more accessible.

00:10:45.832 --> 00:10:48.123
BRANDON SANDERSON: It made
scholarship more accessible.

00:10:48.123 --> 00:10:49.380
That's exactly what it was.

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:51.463
At this time, if you know
anything about Confucian

00:10:51.463 --> 00:10:55.120
society, taking the
tests in Chinese

00:10:55.120 --> 00:10:57.090
to prove how great
you are at Chinese

00:10:57.090 --> 00:10:59.850
is what got you a place
in the government, which

00:10:59.850 --> 00:11:01.280
are the best jobs.

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:02.970
It was a mark of nobility.

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:06.110
And the idea that the
common people could read

00:11:06.110 --> 00:11:10.420
was really a big
deal to the Koreans.

00:11:10.420 --> 00:11:13.914
And it completely causes
a huge revolution.

00:11:13.914 --> 00:11:15.330
There's these
stories, by the way,

00:11:15.330 --> 00:11:17.580
King Sejong writing
Hangul on leaves

00:11:17.580 --> 00:11:20.250
and spreading them through
the air to the people,

00:11:20.250 --> 00:11:22.280
like people would see
it and be like oh,

00:11:22.280 --> 00:11:24.440
and immediately recognize
that this is brilliant

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:26.690
and start being able to write
it because they found it

00:11:26.690 --> 00:11:27.600
on the leaves.

00:11:27.600 --> 00:11:30.290
But years later,
someone, one of the kings

00:11:30.290 --> 00:11:32.560
tried to forbid this
because of this reason

00:11:32.560 --> 00:11:33.960
to keep people from reading it.

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:36.072
By then, in just
a few generations,

00:11:36.072 --> 00:11:37.780
it had become so
pervasive in the culture

00:11:37.780 --> 00:11:40.680
that he couldn't stamp it out,
no matter how hard he tried.

00:11:40.680 --> 00:11:42.540
This stuff is awesome.

00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:46.140
And yet, people tried to keep
everyone else from reading.

00:11:46.140 --> 00:11:47.800
And this is actually a theme.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:49.980
This is a pretty big
theme through history.

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:52.450
The people who tried
to first translate

00:11:52.450 --> 00:11:54.890
the Bible into English,
didn't go so well for them.

00:11:54.890 --> 00:11:56.140
I don't know if you know that.

00:11:56.140 --> 00:11:58.720
But they got burned
at the stake.

00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:01.850
And the resistance
to literacy programs

00:12:01.850 --> 00:12:05.020
in the 1800s in early 1900s
is shocking to us nowadays.

00:12:05.020 --> 00:12:08.580
We're like, why would anyone
not want other people to read.

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:10.210
Well, it's a theme.

00:12:10.210 --> 00:12:13.140
It's something for
some reason that people

00:12:13.140 --> 00:12:15.530
who know something often
want to keep everyone

00:12:15.530 --> 00:12:16.669
else from figuring it out.

00:12:16.669 --> 00:12:18.460
And you might be saying,
OK, Brandon, we're

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:20.510
here at a book signing.

00:12:20.510 --> 00:12:22.000
We work for Google.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:23.940
We're good on this
literacy thing.

00:12:23.940 --> 00:12:26.670
We promised to teach
people to read.

00:12:26.670 --> 00:12:28.940
You're preaching to the choir.

00:12:28.940 --> 00:12:32.400
Well, there's an
issue relating to this

00:12:32.400 --> 00:12:34.880
that has really
started bothering me

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:36.870
over the last few years.

00:12:36.870 --> 00:12:39.290
And I think we're doing
something very similar to what

00:12:39.290 --> 00:12:42.920
these scholars are doing inside
of the science fiction/ fantasy

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:44.480
reading community.

00:12:44.480 --> 00:12:48.690
Let me read you a quote from
a blogger named Bonnie Burton.

00:12:48.690 --> 00:12:50.560
She says, "As a
geek girl, I have

00:12:50.560 --> 00:12:53.350
been accused of wearing a Star
Wars shirt to get attention

00:12:53.350 --> 00:12:55.030
from guys.

00:12:55.030 --> 00:12:58.370
I've been told to move aside
and let real gamers play

00:12:58.370 --> 00:13:00.440
the demos at conventions.

00:13:00.440 --> 00:13:02.670
Lately, it seems elements
of the geek community

00:13:02.670 --> 00:13:04.720
have become a lot less
a welcome wagon and more

00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:09.360
a judgmental jedi council that
refuses to let newbies in,

00:13:09.360 --> 00:13:11.510
especially if they
happen to be girls.

00:13:11.510 --> 00:13:13.800
In a community once known
for celebrating outcasts

00:13:13.800 --> 00:13:15.690
and underdogs, it
sometimes now seems

00:13:15.690 --> 00:13:18.040
like you have to take some
sort of Voight-Kamff test

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:20.420
to prove your geekdom is legit."

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:22.010
And if you didn't
get that reference,

00:13:22.010 --> 00:13:23.540
that is a "Blade
Runner" reference.

00:13:23.540 --> 00:13:27.450
She is totally proving her
geekdom is legit with that one.

00:13:27.450 --> 00:13:29.800
But there's this
sense that you have

00:13:29.800 --> 00:13:32.320
to prove that you are
a true fan to become

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:33.620
part of our community.

00:13:33.620 --> 00:13:34.550
Right?

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:38.330
And this is bigger than
the video game community.

00:13:38.330 --> 00:13:42.740
It's this idea that with
how popular, for instance,

00:13:42.740 --> 00:13:46.600
the comic book movies have
become, I found myself saying,

00:13:46.600 --> 00:13:49.970
you guys are not
true "Iron Man" fans.

00:13:49.970 --> 00:13:52.660
Or my big one was the turtles,
"Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles,"

00:13:52.660 --> 00:13:53.160
right?

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:55.915
I read Eastman and
Laird original run

00:13:55.915 --> 00:13:57.290
of "Teenage Mutant
Ninja Turtles"

00:13:57.290 --> 00:13:59.260
when they all had red masks.

00:13:59.260 --> 00:13:59.920
Right?

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:02.000
This is the way
it's supposed to be.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:03.630
And when it's got
popular, I'm like,

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:05.400
you guys do not
know the Turtles.

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:07.690
You are not fans of my Turtles.

00:14:07.690 --> 00:14:08.820
How dare you?

00:14:08.820 --> 00:14:10.480
Right?

00:14:10.480 --> 00:14:12.189
How many here--
because I've done it.

00:14:12.189 --> 00:14:12.980
I'll raise my hand.

00:14:12.980 --> 00:14:15.950
How many here have
made fun of "Twilight"?

00:14:15.950 --> 00:14:17.830
Yeah.

00:14:17.830 --> 00:14:20.460
Or "Eragon" or
"The Hunger Games,"

00:14:20.460 --> 00:14:23.570
or whatever popular
fiction seems

00:14:23.570 --> 00:14:25.990
to be bringing people into the
science fiction and fantasy

00:14:25.990 --> 00:14:26.823
community at a time.

00:14:26.823 --> 00:14:30.080
For some reason, those of
us entrenched inside of it

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:31.400
get really resistant.

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:34.690
I remember when I was at
science fiction conventions

00:14:34.690 --> 00:14:37.430
in the late 90s, early
2000s, and people

00:14:37.430 --> 00:14:44.390
referred to JK Rowling as
"that damn Scottish woman"

00:14:44.390 --> 00:14:48.240
because all these people
inside the community

00:14:48.240 --> 00:14:50.030
had had this club.

00:14:50.030 --> 00:14:51.480
And suddenly, it was everywhere.

00:14:51.480 --> 00:14:54.170
Now, it's hard to imagine that
now because JK Rowling went on

00:14:54.170 --> 00:14:55.250
to win a Hugo Award.

00:14:55.250 --> 00:14:57.970
She's been very accepted
by the community.

00:14:57.970 --> 00:15:00.560
And yet, initially,
when something

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:03.510
takes off and gets
popular, the community

00:15:03.510 --> 00:15:05.490
wants to push back against it.

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:07.830
And I found myself doing this.

00:15:07.830 --> 00:15:10.500
Now, I want to take an aside.

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:12.536
I'm not saying we
can't criticize.

00:15:12.536 --> 00:15:13.660
In fact, I think we should.

00:15:13.660 --> 00:15:15.280
I have an English degree.

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:18.390
It's four years of learning
to criticize stuff, right?

00:15:18.390 --> 00:15:20.380
It's important to
say, I don't like this

00:15:20.380 --> 00:15:23.320
and this is why, to just
start that discourse,

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:24.450
to have a discussion.

00:15:24.450 --> 00:15:26.950
But what I'm talking
about people doing

00:15:26.950 --> 00:15:33.820
is less about the criticism
and more about the shaming.

00:15:33.820 --> 00:15:34.490
Right?

00:15:34.490 --> 00:15:38.130
It's the kid who gets
on the forums, excited

00:15:38.130 --> 00:15:39.400
because he's read "Eragon."

00:15:39.400 --> 00:15:41.170
And it's like he's
discovered something

00:15:41.170 --> 00:15:42.630
that changed his life.

00:15:42.630 --> 00:15:46.160
And he goes and he posts,
I love the fantasy books.

00:15:46.160 --> 00:15:47.230
I just read "Eragon."

00:15:47.230 --> 00:15:48.840
Can we talk about this?

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:53.040
And the responses, you can see
like 50 responses in a row of,

00:15:53.040 --> 00:15:54.600
why don't you read
something real.

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:55.470
You idiot.

00:15:55.470 --> 00:15:56.810
This is dumb.

00:15:56.810 --> 00:15:59.760
That's just a copy of
"Star Wars," or whatever.

00:15:59.760 --> 00:16:01.350
Just all the way down the list.

00:16:01.350 --> 00:16:02.650
That's what I'm talking about.

00:16:02.650 --> 00:16:05.250
And it's particularly
bad on the internet.

00:16:05.250 --> 00:16:08.820
It's become worse and
worse over the last decade

00:16:08.820 --> 00:16:11.650
because of just how we
are treating one another.

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:16.400
And that hurts me because
fiction is about connecting.

00:16:16.400 --> 00:16:17.400
Right?

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:20.490
I spent several years in higher
education getting a master's

00:16:20.490 --> 00:16:21.710
degree in creative writing.

00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:23.620
And I had to fight every
day to convince them

00:16:23.620 --> 00:16:25.610
that science fiction was legit.

00:16:25.610 --> 00:16:26.370
Right?

00:16:26.370 --> 00:16:28.910
I had professors who refused
to give me good grades

00:16:28.910 --> 00:16:32.360
because I was writing fantasy
novels and turning them in.

00:16:32.360 --> 00:16:34.410
And so to have been
fighting all that and then

00:16:34.410 --> 00:16:36.530
to see our community
doing it to the people who

00:16:36.530 --> 00:16:40.520
are trying to get in and be
part of it really bothers me.

00:16:40.520 --> 00:16:45.270
So this is my plea
and my request.

00:16:45.270 --> 00:16:47.240
Can we be a little less acerbic?

00:16:47.240 --> 00:16:50.700
Can we be a little less
hateful, a little less critical?

00:16:50.700 --> 00:16:52.560
Can we talk about
what we like and don't

00:16:52.560 --> 00:16:55.440
like without dragging
the people who like what

00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:57.630
we don't into the discussion.

00:16:57.630 --> 00:16:58.240
Right?

00:16:58.240 --> 00:17:00.372
Can we keep it about
the fiction and less

00:17:00.372 --> 00:17:01.580
about the people who love it.

00:17:01.580 --> 00:17:04.619
And next time you run into
something that you're like,

00:17:04.619 --> 00:17:08.050
I just don't like
this, maybe instead of

00:17:08.050 --> 00:17:10.750
your first instinct being
to go online and say,

00:17:10.750 --> 00:17:13.990
everyone who likes this
is stupid, maybe give it

00:17:13.990 --> 00:17:15.760
another read, maybe
read through something

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:16.890
you wouldn't have before.

00:17:16.890 --> 00:17:18.140
And you don't have to like it.

00:17:18.140 --> 00:17:20.560
But read through it with
the intent of figuring out

00:17:20.560 --> 00:17:23.500
why other people love it.

00:17:23.500 --> 00:17:26.278
And if you can figure that
out, if you can do that,

00:17:26.278 --> 00:17:28.319
then the fiction is still
fulfilling its purpose.

00:17:28.319 --> 00:17:30.237
It's doing what I did
when I went to Sharjah

00:17:30.237 --> 00:17:31.820
and I was able to
connect with people.

00:17:31.820 --> 00:17:32.890
You can connect
with people who are

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:35.530
different than yourselves, who
like things different than you

00:17:35.530 --> 00:17:36.030
do.

00:17:36.030 --> 00:17:38.526
And if you can figure out
why they love something,

00:17:38.526 --> 00:17:40.650
I think you'll understand
them a little bit better.

00:17:40.650 --> 00:17:42.130
So thank you very much.

00:17:42.130 --> 00:17:47.970
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:47.970 --> 00:17:51.420
So let's go ahead and
do a short Q&amp;A. Anything

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:53.570
you guys are interested
in asking me, go ahead.

00:17:53.570 --> 00:17:55.180
And I'll just repeat
the questions.

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:58.492
That will be easier for the
camera and things like that.

00:17:58.492 --> 00:18:00.450
So whatever you want to
know, I'll answer them.

00:18:00.450 --> 00:18:02.710
And then we'll do the reading.

00:18:02.710 --> 00:18:03.450
Any questions?

00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:04.560
Oh, no questions.

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:05.524
OK, right here.

00:18:05.524 --> 00:18:07.690
AUDIENCE: You're known to
be a very prolific writer.

00:18:07.690 --> 00:18:09.770
What do you attribute
your productivity to?

00:18:09.770 --> 00:18:13.310
BRANDON SANDERSON: So I'm known
to be a very prolific writer.

00:18:13.310 --> 00:18:16.000
To what do I attribute
my productivity?

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:19.290
I can liken this one to Google.

00:18:19.290 --> 00:18:21.260
I remember the first
time I visited Google.

00:18:21.260 --> 00:18:22.610
It was the Seattle campus.

00:18:22.610 --> 00:18:23.300
And I got there.

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:26.060
And they had valet
parking for the engineers.

00:18:26.060 --> 00:18:28.294
And I'm like, valet
parking for the engineers.

00:18:28.294 --> 00:18:28.960
What's going on?

00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:30.960
They're like, well, you
know, it might take them

00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:32.356
a little too long
to find a space

00:18:32.356 --> 00:18:33.480
because it's of tight here.

00:18:33.480 --> 00:18:35.804
We want them to just get
in and start working.

00:18:35.804 --> 00:18:38.220
And then I go in and they have
this full-service cafeteria

00:18:38.220 --> 00:18:39.595
that's serving
this amazing food.

00:18:39.595 --> 00:18:41.140
And I'm like, this is all free?

00:18:41.140 --> 00:18:42.530
And they're like, yeah, yeah.

00:18:42.530 --> 00:18:44.470
And then there's massage tables.

00:18:44.470 --> 00:18:46.020
There's candy.

00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:47.810
And I realized all
they wanted to do

00:18:47.810 --> 00:18:50.560
was keep you there
working and make

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:51.750
you forget what time it was.

00:18:51.750 --> 00:18:52.666
So it's like midnight.

00:18:52.666 --> 00:18:55.550
And you're like, oh, I've just
been enjoying myself so much.

00:18:55.550 --> 00:18:57.984
Or one of the people
joked that it's

00:18:57.984 --> 00:18:59.650
like they start dinner
at a certain time

00:18:59.650 --> 00:19:01.520
so if you get done
working, you're like,

00:19:01.520 --> 00:19:04.690
oh, if I just wait another
hour or two, dinner's here.

00:19:04.690 --> 00:19:05.985
Right?

00:19:05.985 --> 00:19:08.480
And it's all kind of designed
around this idea of keeping

00:19:08.480 --> 00:19:09.880
you happy and working.

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:12.000
That's my life, right?

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:13.920
I love my job.

00:19:13.920 --> 00:19:17.000
And I work from home for
most of the time, which

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:20.260
means that I actually have
plenty of time with my family

00:19:20.260 --> 00:19:23.290
because I work from
about noon until 5:00.

00:19:23.290 --> 00:19:25.810
And I get done, I play
with my kids, my family,

00:19:25.810 --> 00:19:28.830
from about 5:30 to
about 8:30, 9:00.

00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:30.360
And then I go back to work.

00:19:30.360 --> 00:19:34.510
And I work from 9:00 or
10:00 until 3:00 or 4:00.

00:19:34.510 --> 00:19:37.080
And I enjoy my job.

00:19:37.080 --> 00:19:38.620
And I don't have a commute.

00:19:38.620 --> 00:19:39.120
Right?

00:19:39.120 --> 00:19:39.860
I'm just there.

00:19:39.860 --> 00:19:42.880
And it's like, I could
go do something else,

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:44.640
or I could do what I love.

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:47.900
And what I love usually wins.

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:49.540
I'm not that fast a writer.

00:19:49.540 --> 00:19:51.674
But what I am is I'm
a consistent writer.

00:19:51.674 --> 00:19:53.340
And I'm very passionate
about what I do.

00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:57.340
And so I produce around
2,000 words a day, basically

00:19:57.340 --> 00:19:59.110
every day.

00:19:59.110 --> 00:20:01.280
And that just adds up.

00:20:01.280 --> 00:20:02.670
So yep.

00:20:02.670 --> 00:20:03.970
All right, other questions?

00:20:03.970 --> 00:20:04.470
Right there.

00:20:04.470 --> 00:20:05.370
AUDIENCE: How much
of your writing

00:20:05.370 --> 00:20:07.176
do you plot out in advance
and how much unfolds?

00:20:07.176 --> 00:20:08.717
BRANDON SANDERSON:
Oh, good question.

00:20:08.717 --> 00:20:11.590
How much do I plot out in
advance and how much unfolds?

00:20:11.590 --> 00:20:14.650
So most writers fall
somewhere on a spectrum

00:20:14.650 --> 00:20:20.240
between what we call discovery
writers and outline writers.

00:20:20.240 --> 00:20:22.100
George R. Martin has
great terms for these.

00:20:22.100 --> 00:20:25.220
He calls them gardeners
and architects.

00:20:25.220 --> 00:20:27.980
And I am much more an architect.

00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:32.730
I would say about 70/30
on the architect side.

00:20:32.730 --> 00:20:34.400
So what I do is I
build an outline.

00:20:34.400 --> 00:20:35.770
I actually build it in reverse.

00:20:35.770 --> 00:20:38.490
I start with what I
want to have happen.

00:20:38.490 --> 00:20:40.340
And then I work backward.

00:20:40.340 --> 00:20:44.410
And it's not like
Heading A, Subheading

00:20:44.410 --> 00:20:45.370
B. It's not like that.

00:20:45.370 --> 00:20:48.267
What I do is I think, all right,
I've got these two characters.

00:20:48.267 --> 00:20:49.850
What's their
relationship going to be?

00:20:49.850 --> 00:20:51.141
How are they going to interact?

00:20:51.141 --> 00:20:53.270
All right, what's the end goal?

00:20:53.270 --> 00:20:56.490
What do I want the moment
between them at the end to be?

00:20:56.490 --> 00:20:58.072
It can be they don't
like each other.

00:20:58.072 --> 00:20:59.780
It can be they like
each other, whatever.

00:20:59.780 --> 00:21:01.776
I will then brainstorm
steps along the way

00:21:01.776 --> 00:21:02.900
as a list of bullet points.

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:06.330
And I'll do that for every
subplot-- my mystery, how

00:21:06.330 --> 00:21:09.370
does the magic work, a training,
a character becoming better

00:21:09.370 --> 00:21:13.050
at something, any sort of
we need to figure this out.

00:21:13.050 --> 00:21:14.550
And the main one
is usually whatever

00:21:14.550 --> 00:21:16.633
the big plot of the book
is, but all the subplots.

00:21:16.633 --> 00:21:19.720
And so I have all of these
goals and bullet points.

00:21:19.720 --> 00:21:21.002
And that becomes my outline.

00:21:21.002 --> 00:21:23.210
When I work forward, I'm
grabbing these bullet points

00:21:23.210 --> 00:21:25.417
and weaving them in
as I go so that I

00:21:25.417 --> 00:21:27.500
make sure I'm getting all
the proper foreshadowing

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:29.120
for the different subplots.

00:21:29.120 --> 00:21:31.630
I do a lot of planning in my
worldbuilding ahead of time,

00:21:31.630 --> 00:21:33.830
a ton of that.

00:21:33.830 --> 00:21:35.870
Worldbuilding is
very important to me.

00:21:35.870 --> 00:21:38.346
One of the things I've
tried to bring to fantasy

00:21:38.346 --> 00:21:40.720
is I would like to have a
little bit of a science fiction

00:21:40.720 --> 00:21:43.880
rigor for fantasy worlds,
which is not something

00:21:43.880 --> 00:21:46.570
that, as a reader,
I've found a lot of.

00:21:46.570 --> 00:21:48.960
And so it felt like
a hole in the genre

00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:51.080
that I wanted to fill.

00:21:51.080 --> 00:21:54.180
My characters, I do not
do a lot of planning.

00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:55.460
I figure out who they are.

00:21:55.460 --> 00:21:57.860
But usually, I do that
by writing some scenes

00:21:57.860 --> 00:22:00.460
through their viewpoint and
try to explore who they are.

00:22:00.460 --> 00:22:01.290
And then I'm like,
all right, I got

00:22:01.290 --> 00:22:02.760
a feel for who this person is.

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:04.530
Let's build a plot for them.

00:22:04.530 --> 00:22:06.860
But it's very vague
and very loose.

00:22:06.860 --> 00:22:09.230
And that trumps all
the other stuff.

00:22:09.230 --> 00:22:14.200
If I'm writing this character
along and who they're becoming

00:22:14.200 --> 00:22:16.499
would not fulfill the plot
that is planned for them,

00:22:16.499 --> 00:22:18.040
then I have to go
rebuild my outline,

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:20.000
or I have to tear the character
out and put a new character

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:20.583
in that place.

00:22:20.583 --> 00:22:23.650
So I've done both,
depending on the situation.

00:22:23.650 --> 00:22:25.980
And so it's this organic thing.

00:22:25.980 --> 00:22:29.790
And I do that very
intentionally because outline

00:22:29.790 --> 00:22:32.050
writers tend to have a
problem that their endings are

00:22:32.050 --> 00:22:34.250
explosive but their
characters are weak.

00:22:34.250 --> 00:22:36.650
And discovery writers
tend to have weak endings

00:22:36.650 --> 00:22:37.890
and great characters.

00:22:37.890 --> 00:22:39.680
And if you take
that as a guide, you

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:43.730
can usually figure out
who is who in writing.

00:22:43.730 --> 00:22:44.260
Right?

00:22:44.260 --> 00:22:45.295
You usually can.

00:22:45.295 --> 00:22:47.250
You can figure out if they're
more an outline writer or more

00:22:47.250 --> 00:22:48.190
a discovery writer.

00:22:48.190 --> 00:22:51.060
And where books really
start to take off, I feel,

00:22:51.060 --> 00:22:52.820
is where you can
hybridize the two,

00:22:52.820 --> 00:22:55.310
and you can use the discovery
writing for the characters

00:22:55.310 --> 00:22:56.896
and the outlining for the plot.

00:22:56.896 --> 00:22:59.020
And when you can get those
two working really well,

00:22:59.020 --> 00:23:00.590
that's where I
think books really

00:23:00.590 --> 00:23:01.870
start to come together for me.

00:23:01.870 --> 00:23:03.350
So there you are.

00:23:03.350 --> 00:23:04.604
Let's go right here.

00:23:04.604 --> 00:23:06.270
AUDIENCE: So sort of
a related question,

00:23:06.270 --> 00:23:07.970
but on the [INAUDIBLE] level.

00:23:07.970 --> 00:23:10.710
You have this universe
connecting a lot of your books.

00:23:10.710 --> 00:23:12.150
BRANDON SANDERSON: Yes.

00:23:12.150 --> 00:23:14.840
AUDIENCE: To what
extent do you have

00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:16.710
that built out in your head?

00:23:16.710 --> 00:23:17.918
BRANDON SANDERSON: Excellent.

00:23:17.918 --> 00:23:20.170
So I have something
called the Cosmere.

00:23:20.170 --> 00:23:22.350
If you're unfamiliar,
my epic fantasies

00:23:22.350 --> 00:23:26.290
are all connected in
very subtle, minor ways.

00:23:26.290 --> 00:23:28.740
They are cameos from different
characters in each one.

00:23:28.740 --> 00:23:31.867
So any of my books that
don't mention Earth

00:23:31.867 --> 00:23:32.950
tend to be in the Cosmere.

00:23:32.950 --> 00:23:35.440
That's rule of thumb,
what is and what isn't.

00:23:35.440 --> 00:23:39.210
And I'm weaving a few
characters with a hidden epic

00:23:39.210 --> 00:23:41.850
behind the scenes that
I'll eventually get to.

00:23:41.850 --> 00:23:43.520
Right now, it's all
just Easter eggs.

00:23:43.520 --> 00:23:45.960
But because I'm
planning all this,

00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:50.320
I have to have a really solid
outline for the entire Cosmere.

00:23:50.320 --> 00:23:53.240
When I originally plotted it,
it was between 32 and 36 books,

00:23:53.240 --> 00:23:57.390
depending on which books got
split and things like that.

00:23:57.390 --> 00:24:02.730
And yes, I have a pretty
solid outline for all of that.

00:24:02.730 --> 00:24:05.891
The fortunate aspect of
that is remember that it's

00:24:05.891 --> 00:24:07.140
all Easter eggs for right now.

00:24:07.140 --> 00:24:09.350
So you can read the
series out of order.

00:24:09.350 --> 00:24:10.210
It doesn't matter.

00:24:10.210 --> 00:24:11.420
You're not missing anything.

00:24:11.420 --> 00:24:13.753
You just have to watch for
some of these characters that

00:24:13.753 --> 00:24:14.900
are popping in and out.

00:24:14.900 --> 00:24:18.280
And eventually, you'll find more
and more of what they're doing.

00:24:18.280 --> 00:24:20.390
That does require
a lot of plotting.

00:24:20.390 --> 00:24:23.967
And it's something I did because
some of my favorite writers

00:24:23.967 --> 00:24:25.800
connected some of their
worlds late in life.

00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:27.091
And I thought it was brilliant.

00:24:27.091 --> 00:24:28.950
But it also was obvious
they didn't do it

00:24:28.950 --> 00:24:29.550
from the beginning.

00:24:29.550 --> 00:24:30.049
Right?

00:24:30.049 --> 00:24:31.850
Isaac Asimov wove
together the robots

00:24:31.850 --> 00:24:34.540
in "Foundation" in
a really clever way.

00:24:34.540 --> 00:24:36.100
But it wasn't there
from the get go.

00:24:36.100 --> 00:24:38.320
He just figured it
out later on, which

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:41.050
is what you have to do when
you start writing and the 30s

00:24:41.050 --> 00:24:44.860
and you weave them together in
the 70s or something like that.

00:24:44.860 --> 00:24:46.400
But that inspired me.

00:24:46.400 --> 00:24:47.470
I'm like, he's done that.

00:24:47.470 --> 00:24:49.261
Stephen King did the
thing where he kind of

00:24:49.261 --> 00:24:52.090
tied them all together with the
Dark Tower and stuff like this.

00:24:52.090 --> 00:24:55.100
Can I do something from
the get go that plans this?

00:24:55.100 --> 00:24:58.850
And so from "Elantris," my first
book, which was sold in 2003,

00:24:58.850 --> 00:25:01.770
I have all of these kinds of
thing seeded with the idea

00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:04.100
being that there is
an overarching plot

00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:05.020
for the whole thing.

00:25:05.020 --> 00:25:06.180
So it is coming.

00:25:06.180 --> 00:25:08.510
But there's a lot of
that's a ways off.

00:25:08.510 --> 00:25:14.410
The "Mistborn" books are
forming a core for that, which--

00:25:14.410 --> 00:25:17.260
Yeah, I should actually talk
about my book, shouldn't I?

00:25:17.260 --> 00:25:19.580
When I originally pitched
"Mistborn" to my editor,

00:25:19.580 --> 00:25:22.430
I said, I want to do something
I haven't seen in fantasy.

00:25:22.430 --> 00:25:25.160
It's kind of one of
my guiding principles.

00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:26.550
Have I seen it done in fantasy?

00:25:26.550 --> 00:25:28.440
Let's see if we can do it.

00:25:28.440 --> 00:25:30.450
I want to do a
fantasy world that

00:25:30.450 --> 00:25:33.352
evolved into a modern-day
world that eventually evolved

00:25:33.352 --> 00:25:34.560
into a science fiction world.

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:36.330
And the magic becomes
the means by which

00:25:36.330 --> 00:25:37.700
space travel is possible.

00:25:37.700 --> 00:25:38.320
Right?

00:25:38.320 --> 00:25:40.596
And so I wrote this
epic fantasy trilogy.

00:25:40.596 --> 00:25:41.970
And then I jumped
forward and I'm

00:25:41.970 --> 00:25:47.640
kind of doing 1910s era to show
how the fantasy books became

00:25:47.640 --> 00:25:52.480
the foundation of mythology
and history for a modern take.

00:25:52.480 --> 00:25:55.030
And then I'm going
contemporary-ish next.

00:25:55.030 --> 00:25:58.450
I'm really probably
going go in 1980s, kind

00:25:58.450 --> 00:26:02.017
of Tom-Clancy-esque spy epics.

00:26:02.017 --> 00:26:03.350
But you guys will like that one.

00:26:03.350 --> 00:26:05.560
The main character
in that, she's

00:26:05.560 --> 00:26:08.090
a programmer in a
very early programming

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:08.995
language on Scadriel.

00:26:11.940 --> 00:26:17.780
So imagine a programmer who
gets recruited by the CIA

00:26:17.780 --> 00:26:19.470
to go be a field agent.

00:26:19.470 --> 00:26:20.720
It'll make sense when I do it.

00:26:20.720 --> 00:26:24.860
But we will eventually evolve
that into a science fiction

00:26:24.860 --> 00:26:27.090
space epic.

00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:30.272
So that's where I'm
going with those.

00:26:30.272 --> 00:26:32.105
And I should have
mentioned when I did this,

00:26:32.105 --> 00:26:35.160
this was actually the
inspiration for "Elantris."

00:26:35.160 --> 00:26:38.120
This idea of the Chinese
characters and Korean,

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:39.431
because I speak Korean.

00:26:39.431 --> 00:26:40.430
I've been learning this.

00:26:40.430 --> 00:26:41.221
It was really cool.

00:26:41.221 --> 00:26:43.610
And that's why my very first
published book, "Elantris,"

00:26:43.610 --> 00:26:45.970
has this magic system based
around these cool characters

00:26:45.970 --> 00:26:49.140
and the language
surrounding them.

